To implement the singleton pattern in Python using a metaclass, you can define a metaclass that controls the instantiation of classes. Here's an example:

```python
class SingletonMeta(type):
    _instances = {}

    def __call__(cls, *args, **kwargs):
        if cls not in cls._instances:
            cls._instances[cls] = super(SingletonMeta, cls).__call__(*args, **kwargs)
        return cls._instances[cls]

class Singleton(metaclass=SingletonMeta):
    def __init__(self, value):
        self.value = value

# Usage
singleton1 = Singleton("First Instance")
singleton2 = Singleton("Second Instance")

print(singleton1.value)  # Output: First Instance
print(singleton2.value)  # Output: First Instance
print(singleton1 is singleton2)  # Output: True
```

In this example, `SingletonMeta` is a metaclass that overrides the `__call__` method to ensure that only one instance of the `Singleton` class is created. The `Singleton` class uses this metaclass, and any subsequent attempts to create new instances will return the same instance.

```javascript
const fetch = require('node-fetch'); // Import fetch if using Node.js

async function fetchData(urls) {
  try {
    // Create an array of promises using the fetch function
    const promises = urls.map(url => fetch(url).then(response => response.json()));

    // Wait for all promises to resolve using Promise.all
    const results = await Promise.all(promises);

    return results; // Return the array of results
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error fetching data:', error);
  }
}

// Example usage:
const urls = ['https://api.example.com/data1', 'https://api.example.com/data2'];
fetchData(urls).then(data => {
  console.log(data); // Process the fetched data
});
```

In this example, `fetchData` is an async function that takes an array of URLs. It uses `Promise.all` to fetch data from all URLs in parallel. The `fetch` function is used to make HTTP requests, and the results are returned as an array of JSON responses. Note that you need to install the `node-fetch` package if you're using Node.js, as the native `fetch` API is not available in Node.js by default. You can install it using `npm install node-fetch`.

`Promise.all` takes an iterable of promises and returns a single Promise that resolves when all of the input promises have resolved or when the input iterable contains no promises. If any of the input promises reject, the returned promise rejects with the reason of the first promise that rejects.

```javascript
const promise1 = Promise.resolve(3);
const promise2 = 42;
const promise3 = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  setTimeout(resolve, 100, 'foo');
});

Promise.all([promise1, promise2, promise3]).then(values => {
  console.log(values); // [3, 42, "foo"]
}).catch(reason => {
  console.error(reason);
});
```

`Promise.allSettled` returns a promise that resolves after all of the given promises have either resolved or rejected, with an array of objects that each describe the outcome of each promise.

```javascript
const promise1 = Promise.resolve(3);
const promise2 = new Promise((resolve, reject) => setTimeout(reject, 100, 'foo'));

Promise.allSettled([promise1, promise2]).then(results => {
  results.forEach((result) => console.log(result.status)); // "fulfilled" and "rejected"
});
```

`Promise.race` takes an iterable of promises and returns a single Promise that resolves or rejects as soon as one of the input promises resolves or rejects, with the value or reason from that promise.

```javascript
const promise1 = new Promise((resolve, reject) => setTimeout(resolve, 500, 'one'));
const promise2 = new Promise((resolve, reject) => setTimeout(reject, 100, 'two'));

Promise.race([promise1, promise2]).then(value => {
  console.log(value); // "two"
}).catch(reason => {
  console.error(reason);
});
```

To implement retry logic with exponential backoff for a fetch request in JavaScript, you can use the following code example. This example uses the `fetch` API and includes a simple exponential backoff mechanism.

```javascript
async function fetchWithRetry(url, retries = 3, backoff = 300) {
  try {
    const response = await fetch(url);
    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`HTTP error! status: ${response.status}`);
    }
    return response.json(); // or .text(), .blob(), etc., depending on the response type
  } catch (error) {
    if (retries > 0) {
      console.log(`Retrying in ${backoff}ms...`);
      await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, backoff));
      return fetchWithRetry(url, retries - 1, backoff * 2); // Exponential backoff
    } else {
      throw new Error('Max retries reached');
    }
  }
}

// Usage example
fetchWithRetry('https://api.example.com/data', 3, 300)
  .then(data => console.log(data))
  .catch(error => console.error(error));
```

In this code:
- `fetchWithRetry` is an asynchronous function that takes a URL, a number of retries, and an initial backoff time (in milliseconds).
- It attempts to fetch data from the given URL.
- If the fetch fails (e.g., due to network issues), it retries the request with exponential backoff.
- The backoff time doubles with each retry attempt.
- If the maximum number of retries is reached, it throws an error.

Make sure to adjust the `retries` and `backoff` parameters according to your requirements.

To create a debounced search input, you can use the following JavaScript code. This example uses the `setTimeout` function to delay the execution of the search function until the user has stopped typing for 300 milliseconds.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Debounced Search Input</title>
</head>
<body>
    <input type="text" id="searchInput" placeholder="Type to search...">
    <div id="searchResults"></div>

    <script>
        const searchInput = document.getElementById('searchInput');
        const searchResults = document.getElementById('searchResults');

        let timeoutId;

        searchInput.addEventListener('input', () => {
            clearTimeout(timeoutId); // Clear previous timeout

            timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
                const searchTerm = searchInput.value;
                searchResults.textContent = `Searching for: ${searchTerm}`;
                // Here you would typically call your search function
                // searchFunction(searchTerm);
            }, 300); // Wait for 300ms before executing the search
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, the `searchInput` element listens for the `input` event. Each time the user types, the previous timeout is cleared, and a new timeout is set. If the user stops typing for 300 milliseconds, the search function (or any other logic you want to execute) will be triggered. You can replace the `searchResults.textContent` line with your actual search logic.

Event delegation is a technique that leverages the fact that events bubble up in the DOM. Instead of attaching an event listener to each individual element, you can attach a single event listener to a parent element. This listener will handle events for all of its children, even those added dynamically.

Here's an example of how to use event delegation for handling click events on dynamically added list items:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Event Delegation Example</title>
</head>
<body>
    <ul id="myList">
        <li>Item 1</li>
        <li>Item 2</li>
    </ul>
    <button id="addItem">Add Item</button>

    <script>
        // Select the parent element
        const list = document.getElementById('myList');

        // Add click event listener to the parent element
        list.addEventListener('click', function(event) {
            // Check if the clicked element is a list item
            if (event.target && event.target.nodeName === 'LI') {
                console.log('List item clicked:', event.target.textContent);
            }
        });

        // Function to add a new list item
        document.getElementById('addItem').addEventListener('click', function() {
            const newItem = document.createElement('li');
            newItem.textContent = 'New Item';
            list.appendChild(newItem);
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example:
1. We have an unordered list (`<ul>`) with an ID of `myList`.
2. We have a button with an ID of `addItem` that, when clicked, adds a new list item to the list.
3. We attach a single click event listener to the `#myList` element.
4. Inside the event listener, we check if the clicked element is a list item (`<li>`) and log its content.

This way, even if new list items are added dynamically, the event listener on the parent element will still handle the click events for them.

