To create a Node.js Transform stream that converts incoming text to uppercase, you can use the following code:

```javascript
const { Transform } = require('stream');

// Create a Transform stream that converts text to uppercase
const uppercaseTransform = new Transform({
  transform(chunk, encoding, callback) {
    // Convert chunk to uppercase
    const transformedChunk = chunk.toString().toUpperCase();
    // Push the transformed chunk to the readable side
    this.push(transformedChunk);
    callback();
  }
});

// Example usage with readable and writable streams
const { Readable, Writable } = require('stream');

// Create a readable stream
const readableStream = new Readable({
  read(size) {
    this.push('Hello, World!\n');
    this.push(null); // End the stream
  }
});

// Create a writable stream
const writableStream = new Writable({
  write(chunk, encoding, callback) {
    console.log(`Received: ${chunk}`);
    callback();
  }
});

// Pipe the streams together
readableStream.pipe(uppercaseTransform).pipe(writableStream);
```

In this example, we create a Transform stream called `uppercaseTransform` that converts incoming chunks to uppercase. We then create a readable stream that pushes a string to the Transform stream and a writable stream that logs the received chunks. Finally, we pipe the readable stream into the Transform stream and then into the writable stream.

To create a simple HTTP server in Node.js that serves static files and returns a 404 error for missing files, you can use the built-in `http` and `fs` modules. Below is an example of how to set up such a server:

```javascript
const http = require('http');
const fs = require('fs');
const path = require('path');

const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
  // Set the default content type
  res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'text/plain' });

  // Define the directory to serve files from
  const filePath = path.join(__dirname, 'public', req.url === '/' ? 'index.html' : req.url);

  // Check if the file exists
  fs.exists(filePath, (exists) => {
    if (!exists) {
      // If the file doesn't exist, return a 404 error
      res.writeHead(404, { 'Content-Type': 'text/plain' });
      res.end('404 Not Found');
    } else {
      // Read and serve the file
      fs.readFile(filePath, (err, data) => {
        if (err) {
          res.writeHead(500, { 'Content-Type': 'text/plain' });
          res.end('500 Internal Server Error');
        } else {
          res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'text/html' });
          res.end(data);
        }
      });
    }
  });
});

const PORT = 3000;
server.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server running at http://localhost:${PORT}/`);
});
```

In this example, the server serves files from a directory named `public`. If the requested file does not exist, it returns a 404 error. If there's an error reading the file, it returns a 500 error. Otherwise, it serves the file with a 200 status code.

Make sure to create a `public` directory with some files to test the server. You can run this code using Node.js by saving it to a file (e.g., `server.js`) and executing `node server.js` in your terminal.

TypeScript does not have a built-in utility type for making all properties of a nested object optional recursively (DeepPartial). However, you can create a custom utility type called `DeepPartial` as follows:

```typescript
type DeepPartial<T> = {
  [P in keyof T]?: T[P] extends object ? DeepPartial<T[P]> : T[P];
};

// Example usage:
interface Example {
  a: number;
  b: {
    c: string;
    d: number;
  };
}

const example: DeepPartial<Example> = {
  b: { d: 42 }, // 'a' is optional, 'c' is optional, 'd' is required
};

