In Rust, you can define an enum with different variants that hold different data types as follows:

```rust
// Define an enum with different variants
enum MyEnum {
    VariantOne(i32),
    VariantTwo(String),
    VariantThree(bool),
}

// Function to process the enum variants using pattern matching
fn process_enum(value: MyEnum) {
    match value {
        MyEnum::VariantOne(num) => println!("Variant One holds an integer: {}", num),
        MyEnum::VariantTwo(text) => println!("Variant Two holds a string: {}", text),
        MyEnum::VariantThree(flag) => println!("Variant Three holds a boolean: {}", flag),
    }
}

fn main() {
    let my_enum = MyEnum::VariantOne(42);
    let my_enum2 = MyEnum::VariantTwo("Hello, Rust!".to_string());
    let my_enum3 = MyEnum::VariantThree(true);

    process_enum(my_enum);
    process_enum(my_enum2);
    process_enum(my_enum3);
}
```

In this example, `MyEnum` is an enum with three variants, each holding a different data type: an `i32`, a `String`, and a `bool`. The `process_enum` function uses pattern matching to handle each variant appropriately. The `main` function demonstrates creating instances of `MyEnum` and processing them.
